<header class="container-fluid py-2 bg-primary text-light">
  <div class="row">
    <h3 class="col-10 text-center">
      Jay Crowley Engagement Request Process
    </h3>
    <small class="col-2 text-right">
      <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#whatIsThisModal">What is This?</button>
    </small>
  </div>
</header>
<div class="modal fade" id="whatIsThisModal" tabindex="-1" role="dialog" aria-labelledby="#whatIsThisModalLabel" aria-hidden="true">
  <div class="modal-dialog" role="document">
    <div class="modal-content">
      <div class="modal-header">
        <h5 class="modal-title" id="whatIsThisModalLabel">What is This?</h5>
        <button type="button" class="close" data-dismiss="modal" aria-label="Close">
          <span aria-hidden="true">&times;</span>
        </button>
      </div>
      <div class="modal-body">
        <p>
          I work in the tech division of a very large organization.
          As with many very large organizations, there is more than a bit of bureaucracy.
          This web app is roughly based on an actual form in the organization for requesting
          technical help with new projects.  The form itself appeared to be designed so
          that it could not be completed properly.  This allowed the receivers of said form
          to get out of doing any actual work by rejecting all requests.
        </p>
        <p>
          I've been there a long time, and have touched many things, so I often get
          requests out of the blue, from random places in the organization.
          I was joking with colleagues about implementing a request form for myself,
          similar to the forms found for other departments, and this site was born.
          My form is quite a bit prettier than the actual form, believe it or not!
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="modal-footer">
        <button type="button" class="btn btn-primary" data-dismiss="modal">Close</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<nav class="navbar navbar-expand-sm navbar-light border-bottom">
  <button class="navbar-toggler" type="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-target="#navbarNav" aria-controls="navbarSupportedContent" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle navigation">
    <span class="navbar-toggler-icon"></span>
  </button>
  <div class="collapse navbar-collapse">
    <ul class="navbar-nav">
      <li class="nav-item">
        <%=
          # helper to set class of nav item so active is current url
          # is this a good way to do this?  not really sure, but works great!
          def nav_class(path)
            if request.path == path
              'nav-link active'
            else
              'nav-link'
            end
          end

          link_to "Home", root_path, class: nav_class('/')
        %>
      </li>
      <li class="nav-item">
        <%=
          link_to 'New Request', new_engagement_request_path, class: nav_class('/engagement_requests/new')
        %>
      </li>
      <li class="nav-item">
        <a class="nav-link" href="#">Request Status</a>
      </li>
      <li class="nav-item">
        <a class="nav-link" href="#">Employee Directory</a>
      </li>
      <li class="nav-item">
        <a class="nav-link" href="#">Financial Hierarchy</a>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</nav>
